<HEADLINE>
<P>
SEARCH FOR AMERICA LEADS HIM ABROAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Re "Crime Fears Cramp New Yorkers' Style" (Sept. 16): It's not the city. It's 
the nation. New York, Los Angeles, Detroit, Chicago -- over the years the 
nation has grown mean, and, by extension, (so have) its people. 
</P>
<P>
I'm 55 years old, part American Indian. This is my country. I spent 15 years in 
the civil rights movement. I caught a freedom bus in 1960 and went to look for 
America. Meridian, Birmingham, Jackson, Chicago in '68 -- this wasn't the 
America I read about. 
</P>
<P>
And it has grown worse. Children starve, old people have no dignity. No food. 
No homes. Next month, I'm outta here -- putting my van, my cooking equipment, 
my body on a boat to Europe, and my dreams. I plan to open a restaurant in 
Prague and call it the American Dream -- anyone's welcome. Nothing to leave 
behind, except a note on the door: Gone to Czechoslovakia. Gone to look for 
America. 
</P>
<P>
SAL GIANNETTA 
</P>
<P>
North Hollywood 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
