<P>
CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SACRAMENTO; 
</P>
<P>
FLAG HONORING GAYS ORDERED REMOVED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A rainbow-colored flag intended to honor gays and lesbians briefly flew over 
the state Capitol, but it was soon ordered taken down by Gov. George 
Deukmejian's office. Sen. Milton Marks (D-San Francisco), whose district 
contains a large number of gays, asked the Joint Rules Committee to allow the 
flag, which has no writing on it, to be flown and permission was granted. But 
after only a few hours complaints were received by the governor's office and it 
was ordered removed. "Flags that represent special interest lifestyles or 
issues are not to be flown over the state Capitol," said Susan Trowbridge, a 
Deukmejian spokeswoman. 
</P>
