</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ANKARA, Turkey 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Foreign Minister Ali Bozer resigned today in an apparent rift over his virtual 
exclusion by President Turgut Ozal from Turkey's policy over the Persian Gulf 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
"I have resigned because I could not have continued my job with speculation 
about myself," Bozer told a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
He said he handed in his resignation two weeks ago after returning from a visit 
to Washington and New York with Ozal. 
</P>
<P>
Bozer was known to have been dismayed when he was excluded from Ozal's White 
House meeting with President Bush last month. Foreign Ministry officials noted 
that Secretary of State James A. Baker III attended the talks, during which 
Ozal vowed to honor the U.N. economic embargo against Iraq. 
