<P>
ASAHI REVISES DEAL FOR BREWERY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SYDNEY, Australia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Japan's Asahi Breweries, faced with a steep drop in the share price of Elders 
IXL, today revised a $787-million deal to buy a major slice of the world's 
fourth-largest brewer. 
</P>
<P>
Asahi, Japan's second-largest brewer, still plans to buy 19.9% of Elders, but 
it will not buy all the shares from Elders' debt-laden parent, Harlin Holdings. 
</P>
<P>
"Although Asahi still intends to acquire 19.9% of Elders, it plans to acquire 
fewer shares from Harlin and to buy the balance on the market in due course," 
Harlin, which owns 56% of Elders, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
"The basic structure of the original transaction will be preserved," Harlin 
said. "In particular, the transaction will have the effect of stabilizing 
Harlin's financial position." 
</P>
<P>
A sharp rally in Elders' share price today to $1 on a large turnover of almost 
4 million shares prompted speculation that Asahi may already have been 
accumulating in the open market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
