<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOZART PIECE DEBUTS AT AGE 200 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LONDON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An unfinished piece of music by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart has been played, 
possibly for the first time, after a relative decided to auction off the work 
composed about 200 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
Five students at the Royal College of Music on Thursday performed the 35 bars 
of the "Quintet in B Flat Major" for piano and wind instruments -- oboe, 
clarinet, basset horn and bassoon. 
</P>
<P>
"They are an unusual group of instruments, and I think the work might not have 
been completed because Mozart may have found it difficult to find musicians to 
play them," said Stephen Roe, director of manuscripts at Sotheby's. 
</P>
<P>
The firm will auction the music Nov. 21. 
</P>
<P>
The fragment took 1 1/4 minutes to perform and sounded complete, although it 
was only the opening of a work. 
</P>
<P>
Roe said the single sheet of music was on the same kind of paper Mozart was 
using in 1783. He said it was brought to one of their offices on the European 
continent by a member of the family who had preserved it and who asked not to 
be identified. 
</P>
</TEXT>
